 Greek football}}\n{{1988\u201389 in European Football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1988-89 Alpha Ethniki}}\n[[Category:Alpha Ethniki seasons]]\n[[Category:1988\u201389 in European association football leagues|Greece]]\n[[Category:1988\u201389 in Greek football|1]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1988%E2%80%9389_Alpha_Ethniki"}
{"title_page": "Census of India", "text_new": "{{short description|Decennial census mandated by the 1948 Census of India Act}}\nThe decennial '''Census of [[India]]''' has been conducted 15 times, as of 2011. While it has been undertaken every 10 years, beginning in 1872 under British Viceroy Lord Mayo, the first complete census was taken in 1881.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2015/01/09/where-are-indias-census-figures-on-religion/|title=Where Are India\u2019s 2011 Census Figures on Religion?}}</ref> Post 1949, it has been conducted by the [[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India]] under the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]], [[Government of India]]. All the censuses since 1951 were conducted under the 1948 Census of India Act. The last  [[census]] was held in 2011, whilst the next will be held in 2021.\n\n== Census of India prior to Independence ==\n*[[Census of India prior to independence|Overview]]\n*[[1872 Census of india]]\n*[[1881 Census of India]]\n*[[1891 Census of India]]\n*[[1901 Census of India]]\n*[[1911 Census of India]]\n*[[1921 Census of India]]\n*[[1931 Census of India]]\n*[[1941 Census of India]]\n\n== Census of independent India ==\n*[[1951 Census of India]]\n*[[1961 Census of India]]\n*[[1971 Census of India]] \n*[[1981 Census of India]]\n*[[1991 Census of India]]\n*[[2001 Census of India]]\n*[[2011 Census of India]]\n*[[2021 Census of India]]\n\n== References ==\n* [http://omstamps.com/index.php?route=blog/article&article_id=32 Stamps issued by India Post]\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Censuses in India}}\n\n{{Census of India}}\n{{Asia topic|Census in}}\n\n[[Category:Demographics of India]]\n[[Category:Censuses in India| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Decennial census mandated by the 1948 Census of India Act}}\nThe decennial '''Census of [[India]]''' has been conducted 15 times, as of 2011. While it has been undertaken every 10 years, beginning in 1872 under british Viceroy Lord Mayo, the first complete census was taken in 1881.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2015/01/09/where-are-indias-census-figures-on-religion/|title=Where Are India\u2019s 2011 Census Figures on Religion?}}</ref> Post 1949, it has been conducted by the [[Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India]] under the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]], [[Government of India]]. All the censuses since 1951 were conducted under the 1948 Census of India Act. The last  [[census]] was held in 2011, whilst the next will be held in 2021.\n== Census of India prior to Independence ==\n*[[Census of India prior to independence|Overview]]\n*[[1872 Census of india]]\n*[[1881 Census of India]]\n*[[1891 Census of India]]\n*[[1901 Census of India]]\n*[[1911 Census of India]]\n*[[1921 Census of India]]\n*[[1931 Census of India]]\n*[[1941 Census of India]]\n\n== Census of independent India ==\n*[[1951 Census of India]]\n*[[1961 Census of India]]\n*[[1971 Census of India]] \n*[[1981 Census of India]]\n*[[1991 Census of India]]\n*[[2001 Census of India]]\n*[[2011 Census of India]]\n*[[2021 Census of India]]\n\n== References ==\n* [http://omstamps.com/index.php?route=blog/article&article_id=32 Stamps issued by India Post]\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Censuses in India}}\n\n{{Census of India}}\n{{Asia topic|Census in}}\n\n[[Category:Demographics of India]]\n[[Category:Censuses in India| ]]\n", "name_user": "Lakun.patra", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: british \u2192 British", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Census_of_India"}
{"title_page": "Tract housing", "text_new": "{{short description|Type of housing development}}\n[[File:Markham-suburbs aerial-edit2.jpg|thumb|300 px|Aerial view of housing developments near [[Markham, Ontario]], Canada.]]\n'''Tract housing''', also known colloquially in the United States and Canada as '''cookie-cutter housing''', is a type of housing development in which multiple similar homes are built on a tract (area) of land that is [[Subdivision (land)|subdivided]] into individual small [[Land lot|lots]]. Tract housing developments are found in world [[suburb]] developments that were modeled on the [[Levittown, New York#Place in American culture|\"Levittown\"]] concept and sometimes encompass large areas of dozens of square miles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://home.howstuffworks.com/home-improvement/construction/projects/why-cookie-cutter-neighborhoods-exist1.htm|title=Why do cookie-cutter neighborhoods exist?|date=2012-05-02|work=HowStuffWorks|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisoldhouse.com/ideas/15-milestones-changed-housing|title=15 Milestones That Changed Housing|date=2002-03-13|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nTract housing evolved in the 1940s when the demand for cheap housing rocketed. Economies of scale meant that large numbers of identical homes could be built faster and more cheaply to fulfil the growing demand. Developers would purchase a dozen or more adjacent lots and conduct the building construction as an assembly-line process.<ref name=\"Communications1988\">{{cite book|author=Custer, Jack|title=Orange Coast Magazine: Customizing your tract home|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=72AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA160 |date=August 1988|publisher=Emmis Communications|pages=160}}</ref>\n\nTract housing development makes use of few architectural designs, and labor costs are reduced because workers need to learn the skills and movements of constructing only those designs rather than repeat the [[learning curve]]. In addition, as all homes in the [[residential development|development]] will be built at the same time, the cost of purchasing and transporting building supplies may be reduced due to [[economies of scale]]. Components such as [[roof truss]]es, [[plumbing]], and stair systems are often [[Prefabrication|prefabricated]] in factories and installed on-site. This allows builders to offer lower prices, which in turn can make homes affordable to a larger percentage of the population.  Early tract homes were often identical, but many tracts since the late 20th century have several designs and other variations in footprint, roof form, and materials, along with options such as garage bays, for a more diverse appearance.<ref name=\"Communications1988\"/>\n\n==Suburbs==\n[[File:South San Jose (crop).jpg|thumb|300 px|A tract housing development in [[San Jose, California]], United States]]\nThe concept of tract housing is occasionally mocked in North American [[popular culture]] as the basis of [[suburb]]ia; notable examples are the songs \"[[Little Boxes]]\" by [[Malvina Reynolds]], \"[[Suburbia (song)|Suburbia]]\" by the [[Pet Shop Boys]] and \"[[Subdivisions_(song)|Subdivisions]]\" by  [[Rush_(band)|Rush]]. It is also often critiqued by city planners and architects, as its construction tends to overlook required elements of successful community building, instead creating a homogeneous residential neighborhood with no local employment, commerce, services, or attractions within close commuting distance.  This leads to a heavy reliance on automobile travel, as residents are unable to address any of these needs locally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/why-commuting-from-the-burbs-can-be-more-costly-than-living-downtown/article29642363/|title=Why commuting costs can make the \u2019burbs more expensive than living downtown|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=10 April 2018|via=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\n== Housing colonies ==\n[[File:Numbers 341 to 385 Lordship Lane N17.jpg|thumb|300 px|Early 20th-century [[terraced house]]s in [[London]].]]\nIn [[Europe]], the majority of subdivided landstrips are built in the type of [[Terraced house|row housing]] development areas. The model of tract housing had been used widely in the history of [[land reclamation]] in the 17th to 19th century, especially in the [[Netherlands]]. Modern tract housing had been used for [[company town]]s in the 19th to 20th century, especially in the areas of [[coal mining]] that attracted a large number of workers. A tract housing area of this type is colloquially known in German as a \"[[:de:Zechenkolonie|(Zechen-) Kolonie]]\", and in Flemish Dutch and French as a \"cit\u00e9\"[[:nl:Cit\u00e9|(nl)]]/[[:fr:Cit\u00e9 ouvri\u00e8re|(fr)]] or \"coron\"[[:fr:Coron (urbanisme)|(fr)]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Tract housing}}\n* [[Housing estate]]\n* [[List of house styles]]\n* [[List of house types]]\n* [[Railroad apartment]]\n* [[Shotgun house]]\n\n{{Developments}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tract Housing}}\n[[Category:House types]]\n[[Category:Planned residential developments]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Type of housing development}}\n[[File:Markham-suburbs aerial-edit2.jpg|thumb|300 px|Aerial view of housing developments near [[Markham, Ontario]], Canada.]]\n'''Tract housing''', also known colloquially in the United States and Canada as '''cookie-cutter housing''', is a type of housing development in which multiple similar homes are built on a tract (area) of land that is [[Subdivision (land)|subdivided]] into individual small [[Land lot|lots]]. Tract housing developments are found in world [[suburb]] developments that were modeled on the [[Levittown, New York#Place in American culture|\"Levittown\"]] concept and sometimes encompass large areas of dozens of square miles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://home.howstuffworks.com/home-improvement/construction/projects/why-cookie-cutter-neighborhoods-exist1.htm|title=Why do cookie-cutter neighborhoods exist?|date=2012-05-02|work=HowStuffWorks|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thisoldhouse.com/ideas/15-milestones-changed-housing|title=15 Milestones That Changed Housing|date=2002-03-13|access-date=2017-03-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\nTract housing evolved in the 1940s when the demand for cheap housing rocketed. Economies of scale meant that large numbers of identical homes could be built faster and more cheaply to fulfil the growing demand. Developers would purchase a dozen or more adjacent lots and conduct the building construction as an assembly-line process.<ref name=\"Communications1988\">{{cite book|author=Custer, Jack|title=Orange Coast Magazine: Customizing your tract home|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=72AEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA160 |date=August 1988|publisher=Emmis Communications|pages=160}}</ref>\n\nTract housing development makes use of few architectural designs, and labor costs are reduced because workers need to learn the skills and movements of constructing only those designs rather than repeat the [[learning curve]]. In addition, as all homes in the [[residential development|development]] will be built at the same time, the cost of purchasing and transporting building supplies may be reduced due to [[economies of scale]]. Components such as [[roof truss]]es, [[plumbing]], and stair systems are often [[Prefabrication|prefabricated]] in factories and installed on-site. This allows builders to offer lower prices, which in turn can make homes affordable to a larger percentage of the population.  Early tract homes were often identical, but many tracts since the late 20th century have several designs and other variations in footprint, roof form, and materials, along with options such as garage bays, for a more diverse appearance.<ref name=\"Communications1988\"/>\n\n==Suburbs==\n[[File:South San Jose (crop).jpg|thumb|300 px|A tract housing development in [[San Jose, California]], United States]]\nThe concept of tract housing is occasionally mocked in North American [[popular culture]] as the basis of [[suburb]]ia; notable examples are the songs \"[[Little Boxes]]\" by [[Malvina Reynolds]], \"[[Suburbia (song)|Suburbia]]\" by the [[Pet Shop Boys]] and \"[[Subdivisions_(song)|Subdivisions]]\" by  [[Rush_(band)|Rush]]. It is also often critiqued by city planners and architects, as its construction tends to overlook required elements of successful community building, instead creating a homogeneous residential neighborhood with no local employment, commerce, services, or attractions within close commuting distance.  This leads to a heavy reliance on automobile travel, as residents are unable to address any of these needs locally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-investor/why-commuting-from-the-burbs-can-be-more-costly-than-living-downtown/article29642363/|title=Why commuting costs can make the \u2019burbs more expensive than living downtown|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=10 April 2018|via=The Globe and Mail}}</ref>\n\n== Housing colonies ==\n[[File:Numbers 341 to 385 Lordship Lane N17.jpg|thumb|300 px|[[Terraced house]]s in 20th-century style in [[London]].]]\nIn [[Europe]], the majority of subdivided landstrips are built in the type of [[Terraced house|row housing]] development areas. The model of tract housing had been used widely in the history of [[land reclamation]] in the 17th to 19th century, especially in the [[Netherlands]]. Modern tract housing had been used for [[company town]]s in the 19th to 20th century, especially in the areas of [[coal mining]] that attracted a large number of workers. A tract housing area of this type is colloquially known in German as a \"[[:de:Zechenkolonie|(Zechen-) Kolonie]]\", and in Flemish Dutch and French as a \"cit\u00e9\"[[:nl:Cit\u00e9|(nl)]]/[[:fr:Cit\u00e9 ouvri\u00e8re|(fr)]] or \"coron\"[[:fr:Coron (urbanisme)|(fr)]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Tract housing}}\n* [[Housing estate]]\n* [[List of house styles]]\n* [[List of house types]]\n* [[Railroad apartment]]\n* [[Shotgun house]]\n\n{{Developments}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tract Housing}}\n[[Category:House types]]\n[[Category:Planned residential developments]]\n", "name_user": "DoubleGrazing", "label": "safe", "comment": "Not just 20thC, but early 20thC; not just in that style, but actually built then", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tract_housing"}
{"title_page": "Pauserna language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n| name = Pauserna\n| altname = Guarasugw\u00e9\n| nativename = War\u00e1zu\n| region = [[Beni Department]]\n| ethnicity = 46 (2000)<ref name=e15/>\n| extinct = ?\n| ref = e15\n| familycolor = American\n| fam1 = [[Tupian languages|Tupian]]\n| fam2 = [[Tupi\u2013Guarani languages|Tupi\u2013Guarani]]\n| fam3 = Guayaru\n| iso3 = psm\n| glotto = paus1244\n| glottorefname = War\u00e1zu\n| states = [[Bolivia]]\n}}\n\n'''Pauserna''', or '''Guarasugw\u00e9''' (Guaras\u00fa'we, ''War\u00e1zu''), is a moribund <ref>{{cite web|url=https://periodicos.sbu.unicamp.br/ojs/index.php/liames/article/view/8647468/pdf|title=Ramirez, H.; Fran\u00e7a, M.C.V. (2017) O War\u00e1zu do Guapor\u00e9 (tupi-guarani: primeira descri\u00e7\u00e3o lingu\u00edstica. Liames, v. 17, n. 2, p. 1-96.|publisher=}}</ref> [[Tupi\u2013Guaran\u00ed languages|Tupi\u2013Guaran\u00ed language]] of [[Bolivia]]. It is spoken by the [[Guarasugw\u00e9 people]] who number 125 in 2012.<ref name=\"Censo2012\">{{cite web|url=http://inecloud.ine.gob.bo/owncloud/index.php/s/w2ZCFwI7qJrwTwD/download |title=Censo de Poblaci\u00f3n y Vivienda 2012 Bolivia Caracter\u00edsticas de la Poblaci\u00f3n |page = 29 |website = Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Rep\u00fablica de Bolivia}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Languages of Bolivia}}\n{{Tupian languages}}\n[[Category:Tupi\u2013Guarani languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of South America]]\n\n\n{{tupian-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Pauserna\n|altname=Guarasugw\u00e9\n|nativename=War\u00e1zu \n|region=[[Bolivia]]\n|ethnicity=46 (2000)<ref name=e15/>\n|extinct=?\n|ref=e15\n|familycolor=American\n|fam1=[[Tupian languages|Tupian]]\n|fam2=[[Tupi\u2013Guarani languages|Tupi\u2013Guarani]]\n|fam3=Guayaru\n|iso3=psm\n|glotto=paus1244\n|glottorefname=War\u00e1zu\n}}\n\n'''Pauserna''', or '''Guarasugw\u00e9''' (Guaras\u00fa'we, ''War\u00e1zu''), is a moribund <ref>{{cite web|url=https://periodicos.sbu.unicamp.br/ojs/index.php/liames/article/view/8647468/pdf|title=Ramirez, H.; Fran\u00e7a, M.C.V. (2017) O War\u00e1zu do Guapor\u00e9 (tupi-guarani: primeira descri\u00e7\u00e3o lingu\u00edstica. Liames, v. 17, n. 2, p. 1-96.|publisher=}}</ref> [[Tupi\u2013Guaran\u00ed languages|Tupi\u2013Guaran\u00ed language]] of [[Bolivia]]. It is spoken by the [[Guarasugw\u00e9 people]] who number 125 in 2012.<ref name=\"Censo2012\">{{cite web|url=http://inecloud.ine.gob.bo/owncloud/index.php/s/w2ZCFwI7qJrwTwD/download |title=Censo de Poblaci\u00f3n y Vivienda 2012 Bolivia Caracter\u00edsticas de la Poblaci\u00f3n |page = 29 |website = Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Rep\u00fablica de Bolivia}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Languages of Bolivia}}\n{{Tupian languages}}\n[[Category:Tupi\u2013Guarani languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Extinct languages of South America]]\n\n\n{{tupian-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "AEdwards100", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added region to Infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pauserna_language"}
